      <h1 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:clamp(2rem,5vw,3.25rem);font-weight:400;color:#f0ece4;line-height:1.12;letter-spacing:-0.02em;margin-bottom:1.5rem;">
        Selling a Brisbane Property With a Shared Driveway: Easements, Maintenance, and Buyer Concerns
      </h1>
      <p style="font-size:1rem;color:rgba(240,236,228,0.6);line-height:1.8;max-width:54ch;">
        Shared driveways are common on inner-east battle-axe blocks, rear units, and small-lot subdivisions. Here is how to disclose the access, handle the maintenance question, and price for the buyer pool a shared driveway actually attracts.
      </p>
    </div>
  </div>

  <!-- Body -->
  <div style="padding:3rem 0 7rem;">
    <div class="max-w-[780px] mx-auto px-8" style="font-size:0.97rem;color:var(--color-text-secondary);line-height:1.9;display:flex;flex-direction:column;gap:1.75rem;">

      <p>A shared driveway is one of those property features that sounds minor on the listing description and turns out to be the most-asked-about item at every open home. For Brisbane inner-east sellers, it shows up most often on rear-block houses (battle-axe lots created by subdivision in the 1980s and 1990s), on small unit blocks of three or four where the driveway runs past two or three properties to reach a parking area, and on character houses where a side driveway has historically been used by a neighbour despite never being formally split. Each of these scenarios has a different legal structure underneath it, and each produces a different question from buyers.</p>

      <p>This article walks Brisbane sellers through what a shared driveway actually is in legal and practical terms, what you must disclose, how buyers and their solicitors will probe the arrangement, what the value impact tends to be, and how to position the property so the driveway is a fact buyers accept rather than a friction point that derails the sale. The goal is to remove the surprise from the buyer's due diligence by handling the question before they ask it.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">The four shared driveway structures you might have</h2>
      <p><strong style="color:var(--color-text-primary);">Registered easement.</strong> The most common and the cleanest. The driveway sits on one lot (the burdened lot) and gives a registered right of access to one or more other lots (the benefited lots). The easement appears on the title search, has a defined width and length, and usually attaches a sketch plan. Many easements are silent on maintenance; some have an associated easement agreement or deed that addresses cost-sharing, repairs, and use restrictions.</p>

      <p><strong style="color:var(--color-text-primary);">Common property in a community titles scheme.</strong> If your property is part of a unit block or townhouse complex, the driveway is typically common property administered by the body corporate. Maintenance comes out of the body corporate budget, by-laws regulate use (parking, speed, deliveries), and your contract attaches the disclosure documents the buyer needs to assess the running cost. This is the structure with the least seller friction.</p>

      <p><strong style="color:var(--color-text-primary);">Reciprocal easement (crossover easements).</strong> Sometimes both lots burden each other, with each owner having a right of access over part of the other lot. This is most common where the driveway crosses the boundary or where two adjoining houses share a single carport or garage approach. The contract needs to attach both easement documents.</p>

      <p><strong style="color:var(--color-text-primary);">Informal or handshake arrangement.</strong> The driveway is on one lot but has been used by a neighbour for years, sometimes decades, without a registered easement. This is the most fraught structure. The buyer cannot rely on the access continuing, the neighbour may have a prescriptive claim, and the situation typically needs to be either formalised before sale or disclosed and discounted. Buyers and their solicitors will pick this up quickly.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">What buyers actually ask</h2>
      <p>The questions buyers ask about a shared driveway fall into a predictable order, and a seller who can answer the first three crisply almost never has trouble with the rest.</p>

      <p><strong style="color:var(--color-text-primary);">Is the access registered on the title?</strong> The first thing a buyer's solicitor checks. A registered easement provides legal certainty that the access cannot be unilaterally revoked. An unregistered arrangement is treated as a problem until it is formalised.</p>

      <p><strong style="color:var(--color-text-primary);">Who maintains the driveway?</strong> Buyers want to know whether they will be sent a bill for resurfacing the driveway six months after settlement, or whether the cost-sharing terms are clear. The honest answer is sometimes "we usually split it 50-50 and the last bill was $1,800 for a re-seal in 2024", and that is genuinely useful information for a buyer to have.</p>

      <p><strong style="color:var(--color-text-primary);">What is the relationship with the neighbours like?</strong> An open and honest answer here is far more valuable than a polished one. Buyers expect to inherit the neighbour relationship, and they want to know if there are tensions. A history of cooperative joint maintenance is a positive signal; a history of disputes is a discount. Either way, it is better said than hidden.</p>

      <p><strong style="color:var(--color-text-primary);">Are there parking restrictions?</strong> Can the buyer's visitors park on the driveway? Is there a turning area at the end? Is the access width wide enough for a four-wheel-drive or a tradie's van? These practical questions affect the buyer's daily experience.</p>

      <p><strong style="color:var(--color-text-primary);">What happens if the burdened owner sells or develops?</strong> Registered easements bind the land regardless of who owns the burdened lot. Informal arrangements do not. Buyers worry about a future neighbour with different intentions, and a registered easement is the strongest answer to that worry.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">Battle-axe blocks and the rear-house question</h2>
      <p>Brisbane's inner-east has hundreds of battle-axe blocks created when standard suburban lots were subdivided through the 1980s and 1990s. The pattern is recognisable: a front house on a smaller lot facing the street, a long driveway running up the side, and a rear house on a separate lot with its access rights registered as an easement over the front lot's driveway.</p>

      <p>Buyers of the rear house on a battle-axe block ask different questions to buyers of the front. The rear-house buyer wants certainty about access (registered easement, defined width, what happens if the front owner parks across the driveway), maintenance terms (who pays for repairs, who pays for replacement), and the practical experience (can their delivery vans get up the driveway, is there room to turn around at the back, is the garage on their lot or shared).</p>

      <p>The front-house buyer asks the inverse questions. They want to know how often vehicles travel up and down the driveway, whether their use of their own front yard is restricted by the easement, what they can and cannot do on the easement strip (parking, plantings, fencing), and whether the rear-house owner can demand repairs they have to contribute to. The discount applied to a front house with a long shared driveway down the side is real, and it is usually larger than sellers expect.</p>

      <p>For both sides, the pre-listing investment in a clean copy of the registered easement, a written summary of how maintenance has been handled in recent years, and a candid description of the neighbour relationship pays for itself many times over. It moves the buyer's question from "is this going to be a problem" to "yes, that is the structure, here is how it has worked".</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">Disclosure obligations and what buyers' solicitors will check</h2>
      <p>Queensland's seller disclosure regime requires the contract to provide accurate information about easements that affect the lot, with a current title search and copies of registered easement documents attached. A buyer's solicitor will run their own title search, read the easement, check whether any unregistered interests are flagged on the survey plan, and ask the seller's solicitor for the maintenance arrangements in writing.</p>

      <p>If you have an informal or handshake arrangement with a neighbour, that is not on the title and the buyer's solicitor will often ask whether one exists. Withholding the existence of an informal arrangement is risky; if the buyer discovers it after settlement (which they usually will, the first time the neighbour drives past), that becomes a misleading-conduct claim. Better to disclose, document the history, and accept that some buyers will treat it as a discount.</p>

      <p>Active disputes are also disclosable in practical terms. A current QCAT dispute about a damaged driveway, a fencing notice that touches the easement strip, or an unresolved exchange of solicitor letters with the neighbour all need to be raised with your own solicitor before listing. They will shape the disclosure and may shape the contract terms (for example, an indemnity from the seller in respect of an existing dispute).</p>

      <p>For more on the broader Queensland disclosure framework, see our notes on <a href="/insights/seller-disclosure-obligations-queensland" style="color:#f5d07a;">seller disclosure obligations in Queensland</a>, and for context on title checks see <a href="/insights/title-search-selling-property-brisbane" style="color:#f5d07a;">how a Brisbane title search works</a>.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">The maintenance question, in practice</h2>
      <p>Maintenance is where shared driveways usually go wrong, and it is where Brisbane buyers expend the most due-diligence effort. The legal position depends on what the easement document says. Easements registered in the 1990s often say nothing about maintenance, leaving the default common-law position to apply: each benefited owner contributes to reasonable maintenance proportionate to use. Modern easements drafted by solicitors tend to be more specific, with cost-sharing percentages, dispute-resolution clauses, and sometimes a sinking-fund mechanism.</p>

      <p>In practice, most shared driveways in the inner east are maintained by handshake. Neighbours agree to split a re-seal every seven to ten years, or to share a quote when potholes appear. This works while the relationship is functional and breaks down when one side sells, develops, or has a financial change. A buyer asking about maintenance is partly asking a legal question and partly asking a relationship question, and the most useful answer addresses both.</p>

      <p>If you have a written maintenance history (invoices for re-sealing, copies of emails agreeing to share costs, a brief timeline of the last two or three jobs), present it. If you do not, draft a short timeline yourself and have your solicitor confirm it for the contract. Buyers respond well to evidence; they respond poorly to "the neighbour has always paid half" without anything in writing.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">The value impact</h2>
      <p>A shared driveway typically reduces a Brisbane property's value by 2 to 6 percent compared with an otherwise identical property with sole access. The range depends on several factors. A short shared driveway serving two houses with a clean registered easement and a cooperative maintenance history sits at the lower end. A long shared driveway serving four properties with no maintenance terms and a history of disputes sits at the upper end, and sometimes beyond.</p>

      <p>The discount is partly real and partly buyer-pool compression. Some buyers will not consider a shared driveway property at all. Family buyers with multiple cars, buyers who park trade vehicles at home, and buyers who have had a bad shared-driveway experience elsewhere often filter out at the listing stage. The buyers who remain are still a sufficient pool in the inner east, but the campaign needs to be priced and positioned for them.</p>

      <p>The discount does not increase indefinitely with the perceived "problem" level. Once a property has a registered easement with sensible terms and a calm neighbour history, the marginal discount is small. The cliff is between informal arrangements (large discount, small buyer pool, deal risk) and registered easements (modest discount, normal buyer pool, predictable contract). If you have an informal arrangement, the most valuable thing you can do before listing is invest in formalising it, even if it costs $3,000 to $6,000 in legal and survey work.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">Pre-listing actions that pay back</h2>
      <p><strong style="color:var(--color-text-primary);">Order an early title search and read the easement.</strong> Many sellers have not seen the easement document since they bought the property. Read it. Note the width, length, permitted uses, and any maintenance terms. If something is unclear, ask your solicitor before the listing rather than during a buyer's due diligence.</p>

      <p><strong style="color:var(--color-text-primary);">Document the maintenance history.</strong> A one-page summary covering the last five to ten years, with invoices attached where you have them. Buyers love this. It converts a vague concern into a known cost.</p>

      <p><strong style="color:var(--color-text-primary);">Have an honest conversation with the neighbour.</strong> Tell them you are listing. Ask whether they would be willing to confirm the maintenance arrangement in writing if asked by a buyer's solicitor. A cooperative neighbour is one of the strongest signals you can give to a buyer.</p>

      <p><strong style="color:var(--color-text-primary);">Resolve any active disputes.</strong> A live dispute kills more deals than the underlying problem ever would. If there is a fencing issue, a parking complaint, or an unresolved repair argument, get it sorted before you list, even if that means accepting a small loss to clear the matter.</p>

      <p><strong style="color:var(--color-text-primary);">Photograph the driveway well.</strong> A well-shot driveway photo (clear width, good light, neat surface) does more to reassure buyers at the listing stage than three paragraphs of explanation. A poorly-shot driveway photo (narrow, dark, cluttered) creates an impression you then have to undo at every inspection.</p>

      <p><strong style="color:var(--color-text-primary);">Brief your agent.</strong> Your agent should be able to answer the buyer's first three questions about the driveway without checking with you. If they cannot, the campaign loses momentum at every inspection and every callback. A pre-listing briefing pack solves this for the agent at the same time as it solves it for the buyer.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">When to formalise an informal arrangement</h2>
      <p>If your shared access is not on the title, the question is whether to formalise it before listing or sell with it as-is and accept the deeper discount. The math usually favours formalising. Registering an easement (with the neighbour's agreement) typically costs $3,000 to $8,000 including survey, legal, and registration fees, and takes two to three months. The lift in sale price from converting "informal arrangement, possibly disputed" into "registered easement with maintenance terms" is almost always larger than that cost.</p>

      <p>Formalising requires the neighbour's cooperation, and that is sometimes the obstacle. If the neighbour is hostile or unreachable, the legal options narrow to applying for a statutory easement under the Property Law Act, which is more expensive, slower, and adversarial. In that scenario, sellers sometimes choose to sell with disclosure and a larger discount rather than fight.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">A practical pre-listing checklist</h2>
      <p>1. Order a title search and read the easement document and any associated agreement. 2. Compile a maintenance history covering the last five to ten years, with invoices and emails. 3. Check whether any informal arrangements exist that are not on the title, and decide with your solicitor how to handle them. 4. Have a conversation with the neighbour about the listing and the maintenance summary you intend to provide. 5. Resolve any active disputes before listing. 6. Take quality photographs of the driveway. 7. Build a buyer briefing pack (title search, easement, maintenance summary, neighbour confirmation if available). 8. Brief your agent so they can answer questions at the open home without hesitation. 9. Set the price expectation with a clear understanding of the discount range that applies. 10. Be ready to offer the buyer's solicitor a clean information pack on day one rather than producing it under contract pressure.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">The bottom line</h2>
      <p>A shared driveway is a fact, not a flaw. Buyers will accept it if the access is registered, the maintenance terms are clear, the neighbour relationship is calm, and the price reflects the modest compression in the buyer pool. They will resist it if any of those four are weak. The seller's job is to convert the unknowns into knowns before the listing goes live, so that the question buyers ask at the open home is "how has it worked" rather than "what is the catch". The discount for a clean shared driveway is real but small. The discount for a messy one is large enough to justify several thousand dollars of pre-listing legal work. Either way, the worst outcome is letting the buyer discover the issue first.</p>

